caption.body: Taken around 1936 in a Douglas DC-3, this promotional TWA (Transcontinental & Western Air) photo advertises their complimentary meal service. At the time, these planes held up to 21 passengers and cruised at 175â€“200 miles per hour. The DC-3 was unpressurized and flew at lower altitudes than modern pressurized jetliners, usually below 10,000 feet. In spite of often flying around stormy weather, DC-3 flights still encountered plenty of turbulence at these altitudes. Though the food looks delicious, air sickness occurred frequently.  Image: Transcontinental & Western Air (TWA), Douglas DC-3, c. 1936.  Gift of TWA Clipped Wings International, Inc. 2002.113.334
